33 //
34 // The following are explicitly sized versions of common system
35 // structures which appear in the kernel debugger API.
36 //
37 // All of the debugger structures which are exposed to both
38 // sides of the KD API are declared below in explicitly sized
39 // versions as well, with inline converter functions.
40 //
41 
42 //
43 // Macro for sign extending 32 bit addresses into 64 bits
44 //
45 
46 #define COPYSE(p64,p32,f) p64->f = (ULONG64)(LONG64)(LONG)p32->f
47 
48 __inline
49 void
50 ExceptionRecord32To64(
51  IN PEXCEPTION_RECORD32 Ex32,
52  OUT PEXCEPTION_RECORD64 Ex64
53  )
54 {
55  ULONG i;
56  Ex64->ExceptionCode = Ex32->ExceptionCode;
57  Ex64->ExceptionFlags = Ex32->ExceptionFlags;
58  Ex64->ExceptionRecord = Ex32->ExceptionRecord;
59  COPYSE(Ex64,Ex32,ExceptionAddress);
60  Ex64->NumberParameters = Ex32->NumberParameters;
61  for (i = 0; i < EXCEPTION_MAXIMUM_PARAMETERS; i++) {
62  COPYSE(Ex64,Ex32,ExceptionInformation[i]);
63  }
64 }
65 
66 __inline
67 void
68 ExceptionRecord64To32(
69  IN PEXCEPTION_RECORD64 Ex64,
70  OUT PEXCEPTION_RECORD32 Ex32
71  )
72 {
73  ULONG i;
74  Ex32->ExceptionCode = Ex64->ExceptionCode;
75  Ex32->ExceptionFlags = Ex64->ExceptionFlags;
76  Ex32->ExceptionRecord = (ULONG) Ex64->ExceptionRecord;
77  Ex32->ExceptionAddress = (ULONG) Ex64->ExceptionAddress;
78  Ex32->NumberParameters = Ex64->NumberParameters;
79  for (i = 0; i < EXCEPTION_MAXIMUM_PARAMETERS; i++) {
80  Ex32->ExceptionInformation[i] = (ULONG) Ex64->ExceptionInformation[i];
81  }
82 }

90 #define DBGKM_MSG_OVERHEAD \
91  (FIELD_OFFSET(DBGKM_APIMSG, u.Exception) - sizeof(PORT_MESSAGE))
92 
93 #define DBGKM_API_MSG_LENGTH(TypeSize) \
94  ((sizeof(DBGKM_APIMSG) << 16) | (DBGKM_MSG_OVERHEAD + (TypeSize)))
95 
96 #define DBGKM_FORMAT_API_MSG(m,Number,TypeSize) \
97  (m).h.u1.Length = DBGKM_API_MSG_LENGTH((TypeSize)); \
98  (m).h.u2.ZeroInit = LPC_DEBUG_EVENT; \
99  (m).ApiNumber = (Number)

130 __inline
131 void
132 DbgkmException32To64(
133  IN PDBGKM_EXCEPTION32 E32,
134  OUT PDBGKM_EXCEPTION64 E64
135  )
136 {
137  ExceptionRecord32To64(&E32->ExceptionRecord, &E64->ExceptionRecord);
138  E64->FirstChance = E32->FirstChance;
139 }

1639 typedef struct _ARM_CONTEXT {
1640  //
1641  // The flags values within this flag control the contents of
1642  // a CONTEXT record.
1643  //
1644  // If the context record is used as an input parameter, then
1645  // for each portion of the context record controlled by a flag
1646  // whose value is set, it is assumed that that portion of the
1647  // context record contains valid context. If the context record
1648  // is being used to modify a thread's context, then only that
1649  // portion of the threads context will be modified.
1650  //
1651  // If the context record is used as an IN OUT parameter to capture
1652  // the context of a thread, then only those portions of the thread's
1653  // context corresponding to set flags will be returned.
1654  //
1655  // The context record is never used as an OUT only parameter.
1656  //
1657 
1658  ULONG ContextFlags;
1659 
1660  //
1661  // This section is specified/returned if the ContextFlags word contains
1662  // the flag CONTEXT_INTEGER.
1663  //
1664  ULONG R0;
1665  ULONG R1;
1666  ULONG R2;
1667  ULONG R3;
1668  ULONG R4;
1669  ULONG R5;
1670  ULONG R6;
1671  ULONG R7;
1672  ULONG R8;
1673  ULONG R9;
1674  ULONG R10;
1675  ULONG R11;
1676  ULONG R12;
1677 
1678  //
1679  // This section is specified/returned if the ContextFlags word contains
1680  // the flag CONTEXT_CONTROL.
1681  //
1682  ULONG Sp;
1683  ULONG Lr;
1684  ULONG Pc;
1685  ULONG Psr;
1686 } ARM_CONTEXT, *PARM_CONTEXT;

3071 //
3072 // DbgKd APIs are for the portable kernel debugger
3073 //
3074 
3075 //
3076 // KD_PACKETS are the low level data format used in KD. All packets
3077 // begin with a packet leader, byte count, packet type. The sequence
3078 // for accepting a packet is:
3079 //
3080 // - read 4 bytes to get packet leader. If read times out (10 seconds)
3081 // with a short read, or if packet leader is incorrect, then retry
3082 // the read.
3083 //
3084 // - next read 2 byte packet type. If read times out (10 seconds) with
3085 // a short read, or if packet type is bad, then start again looking
3086 // for a packet leader.
3087 //
3088 // - next read 4 byte packet Id. If read times out (10 seconds)
3089 // with a short read, or if packet Id is not what we expect, then
3090 // ask for resend and restart again looking for a packet leader.
3091 //
3092 // - next read 2 byte count. If read times out (10 seconds) with
3093 // a short read, or if byte count is greater than PACKET_MAX_SIZE,
3094 // then start again looking for a packet leader.
3095 //
3096 // - next read 4 byte packet data checksum.
3097 //
3098 // - The packet data immediately follows the packet. There should be
3099 // ByteCount bytes following the packet header. Read the packet
3100 // data, if read times out (10 seconds) then start again looking for
3101 // a packet leader.
3102 //
3103 
3104 
3105 typedef struct _KD_PACKET {
3106  ULONG PacketLeader;
3107  USHORT PacketType;
3108  USHORT ByteCount;
3109  ULONG PacketId;
3110  ULONG Checksum;
3111 } KD_PACKET, *PKD_PACKET;
3112 
3113

3115 #define INITIAL_PACKET_ID 0x80800000 // Don't use 0
3116 #define SYNC_PACKET_ID 0x00000800 // Or in with INITIAL_PACKET_ID
3117  // to force a packet ID reset.

3861 __inline
3862 ULONG
3863 DbgkdManipulateState32To64(
3864  IN PDBGKD_MANIPULATE_STATE32 r32,
3865  OUT PDBGKD_MANIPULATE_STATE64 r64,
3866  OUT PULONG AdditionalDataSize
3867  )
3868 {
3869  r64->ApiNumber = r32->ApiNumber;
3870  r64->ProcessorLevel = r32->ProcessorLevel;
3871  r64->Processor = r32->Processor;
3872  r64->ReturnStatus = r32->ReturnStatus;
3873 
3874  *AdditionalDataSize = 0;
3875 
3876  //
3877  // translate the messages which may be sent by the kernel
3878  //
3879 
3880  switch (r64->ApiNumber) {
3881 
3882  case DbgKdSetContextApi:
3883  case DbgKdRestoreBreakPointApi:
3884  case DbgKdContinueApi:
3885  case DbgKdContinueApi2:
3886  case DbgKdRebootApi:
3887  case DbgKdClearSpecialCallsApi:
3888  case DbgKdRestoreBreakPointExApi:
3889  case DbgKdCauseBugCheckApi:
3890  case DbgKdSwitchProcessor:
3891  case DbgKdWriteMachineSpecificRegister:
3892  case DbgKdWriteIoSpaceApi:
3893  case DbgKdSetSpecialCallApi:
3894  case DbgKdSetInternalBreakPointApi:
3895  case DbgKdWriteIoSpaceExtendedApi:
3896  break;
3897 
3898 
3899 
3900  case DbgKdReadMachineSpecificRegister:
3901  r64->u.ReadWriteMsr = r32->u.ReadWriteMsr;
3902  break;
3903 
3904  //
3905  // GetVersion may need to be handled by the calling code;
3906  // it needs to call DbgkdGetVersion32To64 with the DebuggerDataBlock.
3907  //
3908 
3909  case DbgKdGetVersionApi:
3910  break;
3911 
3912  case DbgKdGetContextApi:
3913  *AdditionalDataSize = sizeof(CONTEXT);
3914  break;
3915 
3916  //case DbgKdQuerySpecialCallsApi:
3917  // r64->u.QuerySpecialCalls = r32->u.QuerySpecialCalls;
3918  // *AdditionalDataSize = r64->u.QuerySpecialCalls.NumberOfSpecialCalls * sizeof(ULONG);
3919  // break;
3920 
3921  case DbgKdWriteBreakPointExApi:
3922  r64->u.BreakPointEx = r32->u.BreakPointEx;
3923  *AdditionalDataSize = r64->u.BreakPointEx.BreakPointCount * sizeof(ULONG);
3924  break;
3925 
3926  case DbgKdReadVirtualMemoryApi:
3927  case DbgKdReadPhysicalMemoryApi:
3928  case DbgKdReadControlSpaceApi:
3929  DbgkdReadMemory32To64(&r32->u.ReadMemory, &r64->u.ReadMemory);
3930  if (NT_SUCCESS(r32->ReturnStatus)) {
3931  *AdditionalDataSize = r64->u.ReadMemory.ActualBytesRead;
3932  }
3933  break;
3934 
3935  case DbgKdWriteVirtualMemoryApi:
3936  case DbgKdWritePhysicalMemoryApi:
3937  case DbgKdWriteControlSpaceApi:
3938  DbgkdWriteMemory32To64(&r32->u.WriteMemory, &r64->u.WriteMemory);
3939  break;
3940 
3941 
3942 
3943  case DbgKdWriteBreakPointApi:
3944  DbgkdWriteBreakpoint32To64(&r32->u.WriteBreakPoint, &r64->u.WriteBreakPoint);
3945  break;
3946 
3947  case DbgKdReadIoSpaceApi:
3948  DbgkdReadWriteIo32To64(&r32->u.ReadWriteIo, &r64->u.ReadWriteIo);
3949  break;
3950 
3951  case DbgKdReadIoSpaceExtendedApi:
3952  DbgkdReadWriteIoExtended32To64(&r32->u.ReadWriteIoExtended, &r64->u.ReadWriteIoExtended);
3953  break;
3954 
3955  case DbgKdGetInternalBreakPointApi:
3956  DbgkdGetInternalBreakpoint32To64(&r32->u.GetInternalBreakpoint, &r64->u.GetInternalBreakpoint);
3957  break;
3958 
3959  case DbgKdSearchMemoryApi:
3960  r64->u.SearchMemory = r32->u.SearchMemory;
3961  break;
3962  }
3963 
3964  return sizeof(DBGKD_MANIPULATE_STATE64);
3965 }

4031  break;

4033  //
4034  // 32 bit systems only support 32 bit physical r/w
4035  //
4036  case DbgKdReadControlSpaceApi:
4037  case DbgKdReadVirtualMemoryApi:
4038  case DbgKdReadPhysicalMemoryApi:
4039  DbgkdReadMemory64To32(&r64->u.ReadMemory, &r32->u.ReadMemory);
4040  break;

4048  break;

4052  break;

4056  DbgkdReadWriteIo64To32(&r64->u.ReadWriteIo, &r32->u.ReadWriteIo);
4057  break;
4058 
4059  case DbgKdSetSpecialCallApi:
4060  DbgkdSetSpecialCall64To32(&r64->u.SetSpecialCall, &r32->u.SetSpecialCall);
4061  break;
4062 
4063  case DbgKdSetInternalBreakPointApi:
4064  DbgkdSetInternalBreakpoint64To32(&r64->u.SetInternalBreakpoint, &r32->u.SetInternalBreakpoint);
4065  break;
4066 
4067  case DbgKdGetInternalBreakPointApi:
4068  DbgkdGetInternalBreakpoint64To32(&r64->u.GetInternalBreakpoint, &r32->u.GetInternalBreakpoint);
4069  break;
4070 
4071  case DbgKdReadIoSpaceExtendedApi:
4072  case DbgKdWriteIoSpaceExtendedApi:
4073  DbgkdReadWriteIoExtended64To32(&r64->u.ReadWriteIoExtended, &r32->u.ReadWriteIoExtended);
4074  break;
4075 
4076  case DbgKdSearchMemoryApi:
4077  r32->u.SearchMemory = r64->u.SearchMemory;
4078  break;
4079  }
4080 
4081  return sizeof(DBGKD_MANIPULATE_STATE32);
4082 }
4083 
4084 //
4085 // This is the format for the trace data passed back from the kernel to
4086 // the debugger to describe multiple calls that have returned since the
4087 // last trip back. The basic format is that there are a bunch of these
4088 // (4 byte) unions stuck together. Each union is of one of two types: a
4089 // 4 byte unsigned long integer, or a three field struct, describing a
4090 // call (where "call" is delimited by returning or exiting the symbol
4091 // scope). If the number of instructions executed is too big to fit
4092 // into a USHORT -1, then the Instructions field has
4093 // TRACE_DATA_INSTRUCTIONS_BIG and the next union is a LongNumber
4094 // containing the real number of instructions executed.
4095 //
4096 // The very first union returned in each callback is a LongNumber
4097 // containing the number of unions returned (including the "size"
4098 // record, so it's always at least 1 even if there's no data to return).
4099 //
4100 // This is all returned to the debugger when one of two things
4101 // happens:
4102 //
4103 // 1) The pc moves out of all defined symbol ranges
4104 // 2) The buffer of trace data entries is filled.
4105 //
4106 // The "trace done" case is hacked around on the debugger side. It
4107 // guarantees that the pc address that indicates a trace exit never
4108 // winds up in a defined symbol range.
4109 //
4110 // The only other complexity in this system is handling the SymbolNumber
4111 // table. This table is kept in parallel by the kernel and the
4112 // debugger. When the PC exits a known symbol range, the Begin and End
4113 // symbol ranges are set by the debugger and are allocated to the next
4114 // symbol slot upon return. "The next symbol slot" means the numerical
4115 // next slot number, unless we've filled all slots, in which case it is
4116 // #0. (ie., allocation is cyclic and not LRU or something). The
4117 // SymbolNumber table is flushed when a SpecialCalls call is made (ie.,
4118 // at the beginning of the WatchTrace).
4119 //
4120 
4121 typedef union _DBGKD_TRACE_DATA {
4122  struct {
4123  UCHAR SymbolNumber;
4124  CHAR LevelChange;
4125  USHORT Instructions;
4126  } s;
4127  ULONG LongNumber;
4128 } DBGKD_TRACE_DATA, *PDBGKD_TRACE_DATA;
4129 
4130 #define TRACE_DATA_INSTRUCTIONS_BIG 0xffff
4131 
4132 #define TRACE_DATA_BUFFER_MAX_SIZE 40
4133
